{
  "doc_id": "48212",
  "text": "Early studies on WMS claimed that people with WMS do not show the inversion effect and hence fail to process faces holistically [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . However, these studies included small samples of widely varying ages and ability levels. [CITATION_3] used the same whole-part task employed by [CITATION_4] with a large group of adolescents and adults with WMS and age-matched controls. Both groups showed the same pattern of results: better performance in the wholeface condition for upright but not inverted faces. This pattern held for all face features, including the eyes, and provided strong evidence that people with WMS process faces holistically. There is still a debate over whether people with WMS are impaired in configural processing of higher order relations in faces [CITATION_5] . However, this impairment may be more related to developmental delays and mental retardation than to syndrome-specific differences in face processing mechanisms.",
